|}

See also [[Arabic_alphabet#Additional_letters|Additional letters]] below.

====Further notes====
* The letter ''{{transl|ar|DIN|ʾalif}}'' originated in the [[Phoenician alphabet]] as a consonant-sign indicating the [[glottal stop]] {{IPA|[ʔ]}}. Today it has lost its function as a consonant, and, together with  ''{{transl|ar|DIN|yaʾ}}'' and  ''{{transl|ar|DIN|wāw}}'', is a ''[[mater lectionis]]'', a consonant sign standing in for a long vowel (see below), or as support for certain diacritics (''{{transl|ar|DIN|maddah}}'' and ''[[hamza|{{transl|ar|DIN|hamzah}}]]'').

* The shape of the final ''{{transl|ar|DIN|yāʾ}}'' is always undotted &lt;big&gt;{{lang|ar|[[ى]]}}&lt;/big&gt; in both print and handwriting in Egypt and Sudan, mainly.

* Arabic currently uses a diacritic sign, &lt;span style=&quot;font-size:150%;&quot;&gt; {{rtl-lang|ar|ﺀ}}&lt;/span&gt;, called ''[[hamza|{{transl|ar|DIN|hamzah}}]]'', to denote the glottal stop, written alone or with a carrier:
** alone: {{rtl-lang|ar|ء}} ;
** with a carrier: {{rtl-lang|ar|إ أ}} (above or under a ''{{transl|ar|DIN|ʾalif}}''), {{rtl-lang|ar|ؤ}} (above a ''{{transl|ar|DIN|wāw}}''), {{rtl-lang|ar|ئ}} (above a dotless ''{{transl|ar|DIN|yāʾ}}''  or ''{{transl|ar|DIN|yāʾ hamzah}}'').

* Letters lacking an initial or medial version are never linked to the letter that follows, even within a word. The ''{{transl|ar|DIN|hamzah}}'' has a single form, since it is never linked to a preceding or following letter.  However, it is sometimes combined with a ''{{transl|ar|DIN|wāw}}'', ''{{transl|ar|DIN|yāʾ}}'', or ''{{transl|ar|DIN|ʾalif}}'', and in that case the carrier behaves like an ordinary ''{{transl|ar|DIN|wāw}}'', ''{{transl|ar|DIN|yāʾ}}'', or ''{{transl|ar|DIN|ʾalif}}''.

In academic work, the glottal stop {{IPA|[ʔ]}} is transliterated with the [[ʾ|right half ring]] sign ('''&lt;big&gt;{{transl|sem|ʾ}}&lt;/big&gt;'''), while the [[ʿ|left half ring sign]] ('''&lt;big&gt;{{transl|sem|ʿ}}&lt;/big&gt;''') represents a different letter, with a different pronunciation, called [[Ayin|''{{transl|ar|DIN|ʿayin}}'']].

====Modified letters====
The following are not individual letters, but rather different contextual variants of some of the Arabic letters.

