|-
!General&lt;br /&gt;Unicode
!Name
!Transliteration
|- style=&quot;text-align:center;&quot;
|style=&quot;line-height:180%;padding:10px;&quot;|&lt;small&gt;0651&lt;/small&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;font size=&quot;5&quot;&gt;{{rtl-lang|ar|  ّ  }}&lt;/font&gt;&lt;sup&gt;&lt;big style=&quot;color:#ccc;&quot;&gt; ّ &lt;/big&gt;&lt;/sup&gt;
|{{transl|ar|DIN|šaddah}}
|(consonant doubled)
|}

====Nunation====
{{Main|Nunation}}
&lt;div style=&quot;float:left; padding: 0pt 5pt 0pt 0pt&quot;&gt;
{|class=&quot;wikitable&quot;
|-
! Symbol
|style=&quot;line-height:180%;padding:10px;&quot;|&lt;br&gt;&lt;font size=&quot;+3&quot;&gt;{{rtl-lang|ar|  ـٌ  }}&lt;/font&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
!style=&quot;line-height:180%;padding:10px;&quot;|&lt;br&gt;&lt;font size=&quot;+3&quot;&gt;{{rtl-lang|ar|  ـٍ  }}&lt;/font&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
!style=&quot;line-height:180%;padding:10px;&quot;|&lt;br&gt;&lt;font size=&quot;+3&quot;&gt;{{rtl-lang|ar|  ـً  }}&lt;/font&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
|- style=&quot;text-align:center;&quot;
! Transliteration
|colspan=&quot;1&quot;|&lt;br&gt;{{transl|ar|DIN|-un}}
|rowspan=&quot;1&quot;|&lt;br&gt;{{transl|ar|DIN|-in}}
|rowspan=&quot;1&quot;|&lt;br&gt;{{transl|ar|DIN|-an}}
|}
&lt;/div&gt;
Nunation (the Arabic term is {{lang|ar|تنوين}}, ''{{transl|ar|DIN|tanwīn}}'')  is the addition of a final ''{{transl|ar|DIN|-n}}'' to a [[noun]] or [[adjective]]. The vowel before it indicates [[grammatical case]]. In written Arabic nunation is indicated by doubling the vowel diacritic at the end of the word. There are three of these vowel diacritics, and the signs indicate, from left to right, the endings ''{{transl|ar|DIN|-un}}'' ([[nominative case]]), ''{{transl|ar|DIN|-in}}'' ([[genitive]]), and ''{{transl|ar|DIN|-an}}'' ([[accusative]]). The sign {{rtl-lang|ar|ـً}} is most commonly written in combination with {{rtl-lang|ar|ا}} ''{{transl|ar|DIN|ʾalif}}'' ({{rtl-lang|ar|ـًا}}), {{rtl-lang|ar|ةً}} (''[[Ta' marbuta|{{transl|ar|DIN|tāʾ marbūṭah}}]]'' {{lang|ar|تاء مربوطة}}) or stand-alone {{rtl-lang|ar|ءً}} (''[[hamza|{{transl|ar|DIN|hamzah}}]]'' {{lang|ar|همزة}}). An ''{{transl|ar|DIN|ʾalif}}'' should always be written unless the word ends in ''{{transl|ar|DIN|tāʾ marbūṭah}}'', ''{{transl|ar|DIN|hamzah}}'' or is a [[diptote]], even though the ''{{transl|ar|DIN|-un}}'', ''{{transl|ar|DIN|-an}}'' or ''{{transl|ar|DIN|-in}}'' is not written. Nunation is used only in literary Arabic; it is absent in everyday [[varieties of Arabic|spoken Arabic]], and many Arabic textbooks introduce even literary Arabic without these endings.

== Vowels ==
Users of Arabic usually write [[vowel length|long vowels]] but omit short ones, so readers must utilize their knowledge of the language in order to supply the missing vowels. However, in the education system and particularly in classes on Arabic grammar these vowels are used since they are crucial to the grammar. An Arabic sentence can have a completely different meaning by a subtle change of the vowels. This is why in an important text such as the ''{{transl|ar|DIN|Qurʾān}}'' the vowels are mandated.

===Short vowels===
{{See|Arabic diacritics}}

Vowels are conveyed by diacritical marks placed above or below the letters. In the Arabic handwriting of everyday use, in general publications, and on street signs, short vowels are typically not written. On the other hand, copies of the ''{{transl|ar|DIN|Qurʾān}}'' cannot be endorsed by the religious institutes that review them unless the diacritics are included.  It is also generally preferred and customary that they be included whenever the ''{{transl|ar|DIN|Qurʾān}}'' is cited in print.  Children's books, elementary-school texts, and Arabic-language grammars in general will include diacritics to some degree.  These are known as &quot;[[Arabic diacritics|vocalized]]&quot; texts.

Written Arabic cannot be considered truly complete{{By whom|date=November 2010}} without the notation of its short vowels, which are essential to it.  They convey information not coded in any other way. Like dotted letters, diacritical marks were a later addition to the original writing system.

Short vowels can be included in cases where readers could not easily resolve word ambiguity from context alone, or simply wherever their writing might be considered [[calligraphy|aesthetically pleasing]].

Short vowels may be written with [[diacritic]]s placed above or below the consonant that precedes them in the syllable, called ''harakat''. All Arabic vowels, long and short, follow a consonant; in Arabic, words like &quot;Ali&quot; or &quot;alif&quot;, for example, start with a consonant: ''{{transl|ar|ʿAliyy}}''&lt;!--not DIN 31635 transliteration--&gt;, ''{{transl|ar|DIN|ʾalif}}''.

