===Long vowels===
In the fully [[Arabic diacritics|vocalized]] Arabic text found in texts such as [[Koran]], a long ''{{transl|ar|DIN|ā}}'' following a consonant other than a ''[[hamza|{{transl|ar|DIN|hamzah}}]]'' is written with a short ''{{transl|ar|DIN|a}}'' sign (''{{transl|ar|DIN|fatḥah}}'') on the consonant plus an ''{{transl|ar|DIN|ʾalif}}'' after it; long ''{{transl|ar|DIN|ī}}'' is written as a sign for short ''{{transl|ar|DIN|i}}'' (''{{transl|ar|DIN|kasrah}}'') plus a {{transl|ar|DIN|''yāʾ''}} ; and long ''{{transl|ar|DIN|ū}}'' as a sign for short ''{{transl|ar|DIN|u}}'' (''{{transl|ar|DIN|ḍammah}}'') plus a ''{{transl|ar|DIN|wāw}}''. Briefly, ''{{transl|ar|ᵃa}}'' = ''{{transl|ar|DIN|ā}}'', ''{{transl|ar|ⁱy}}'' = ''{{transl|ar|DIN|ī}}'' and ''{{transl|ar|ᵘw}}'' = ''{{transl|ar|DIN|ū}}''. Long ''{{transl|ar|DIN|ā}}'' following a ''{{transl|ar|DIN|hamzah}}'' may be represented by an ''{{transl|ar|DIN|ʾalif maddah}}'' or by a free ''{{transl|ar|DIN|hamzah}}'' followed by an ''{{transl|ar|DIN|ʾalif}}''.

The table below shows vowels placed above or below a dotted circle replacing a primary consonant letter or a [[Shadda|''{{transl|ar|DIN|šaddah}}'']] sign. For clarity in the table, the primary letters on the left used to mark these long vowels are shown only in their isolated form. Please note that most consonants do connect to the left with ''{{transl|ar|DIN|ʾalif}}'', ''{{transl|ar|DIN|wāw}}'' and ''{{transl|ar|DIN|yāʾ}}'' written then with their medial or final form. Additionally, the letter ''{{transl|ar|DIN|yāʾ}}'' in the last row may connect to the letter on its left, and then will use a medial or initial form. Use the table of primary letters to look at their actual glyph and joining types.

{|class=&quot;wikitable&quot;
|-
!Long vowels&lt;br /&gt;(fully vocalised text)
!Name
!Trans.
!Value
|- style=&quot;text-align:center;&quot;
|style=&quot;line-height:180%;padding:10px;&quot;|&lt;small&gt;064E 0627&lt;/small&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;font size=&quot;5&quot;&gt;{{rtl-lang|ar|  َا  }}&lt;/font&gt;&lt;sup&gt;&lt;small style=&quot;color:#ccc;&quot;&gt;◌&lt;/small&gt;&lt;/sup&gt;
|{{transl|ar|DIN|fatḥah ʾalif}}
|''{{transl|ar|DIN|ā}}''
|{{IPA|/aː/}}
|- style=&quot;text-align:center;&quot;
|style=&quot;line-height:180%;padding:10px;&quot;|&lt;small&gt;064E 0649&lt;/small&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;font size=&quot;5&quot;&gt;{{rtl-lang|ar|  َى  }}&lt;/font&gt;&lt;sup&gt;&lt;small style=&quot;color:#ccc;&quot;&gt;◌&lt;/small&gt;&lt;/sup&gt;
|{{transl|ar|DIN|fatḥah ʾalif maqṣūrah}}
|''{{transl|ar|DIN|ā}}'' / ''{{transl|ar|aỳ}}''
|{{IPA|/a/}}
|- style=&quot;text-align:center;&quot;
|style=&quot;line-height:180%;padding:10px;&quot;|&lt;small&gt;064F 0648&lt;/small&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;font size=&quot;5&quot;&gt;{{rtl-lang|ar|  ُو  }}&lt;/font&gt;&lt;sup&gt;&lt;small style=&quot;color:#ccc;&quot;&gt;◌&lt;/small&gt;&lt;/sup&gt;
|{{transl|ar|DIN|ḍammah wāw}}
|''{{transl|ar|DIN|ū}}'' / ''{{transl|ar|uw}}''
|{{IPA|/uː/}}
|- style=&quot;text-align:center;&quot;
|style=&quot;line-height:180%;padding:10px;&quot;|&lt;small&gt;0650 064A&lt;/small&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;font size=&quot;5&quot;&gt;{{rtl-lang|ar|  ِي  }}&lt;/font&gt;&lt;sup&gt;&lt;small style=&quot;color:#ccc;&quot;&gt;◌&lt;/small&gt;&lt;/sup&gt;
|{{transl|ar|DIN|kasrah yāʾ}}
|''{{transl|ar|DIN|ī}}'' / ''{{transl|ar|iy}}''
|{{IPA|/iː/}}
|}

In unvocalized text (one in which the short vowels are not marked), the long vowels are represented by the vowel in question: ''{{transl|ar|DIN|ʾalif}}'', ''{{transl|ar|DIN|ʾalif maqṣūrah}}'' (or ''{{transl|ar|DIN|yaʾ}}''), ''{{transl|ar|DIN|wāw}}'', or ''{{transl|ar|DIN|yāʾ}}''. Long vowels written in the middle of a word of unvocalized text are treated like consonants with a ''{{transl|ar|DIN|sukūn}}'' (see below) in a text that has full diacritics. Here also, the table shows long vowel letters only in isolated form for clarity.

Combinations {{rtl-lang|ar|وا}} and {{rtl-lang|ar|يا}} are always pronounced ''{{transl|ar|DIN|wā}}'' and ''{{transl|ar|DIN|yā}}'' respectively, the exception is when {{rtl-lang|ar|وا}} is the verb ending, where {{transl|ar|DIN|ʾalif}} is silent, resulting in ''{{transl|ar|DIN|ū}}''.

