===Vowel omission===
An Arabic [[syllable]] can be open (ending with a vowel) or closed (ending with a consonant):

* open: CV [consonant-vowel] (long or short vowel)
* closed: CVC (short vowel only)

In closed syllables, we can indicate that the closing consonant does not carry a vowel by marking it with a [[diacritic]] called ''{{transl|ar|DIN|sukūn}}'' ( {{lang|ar|  ْ  }} ) to remove any ambiguity, especially when the text is not vocalized. A normal text is composed only of series of consonants; thus, the word ''{{transl|ar|DIN|qalb}}'', &quot;heart&quot;, is written ''{{transl|ar|qlb}}''. The ''{{transl|ar|DIN|sukūn}}'' indicates where not to place a vowel: ''{{transl|ar|qlb}}'' could, in effect, be read ''{{transl|ar|DIN|qalab}}'' (meaning &quot;he turned around&quot;), but written with a ''{{transl|ar|DIN|sukūn}}'' over the ''{{transl|ar|l}}'' and the ''{{transl|ar|b}}'' ({{rtl-lang|ar|قلْبْ}}), it can only have the form ''{{transl|ar|qVlb}}''. This is one step down from full vocalization, where the vowel ''{{transl|ar|DIN|a}}'' would also be indicated by a ''{{transl|ar|DIN|fatḥah}}'': {{rtl-lang|ar|قَلْبْ}}.

The ''{{transl|ar|DIN|[[Qurʾān]]}}'' is traditionally written in full vocalization. Outside of the ''{{transl|ar|DIN|Qurʾān}}'', putting a ''{{transl|ar|DIN|sukūn}}'' above a ''{{transl|ar|DIN|yāʾ}}'' (representing {{IPA|/iː/}}), or above a ''{{transl|ar|DIN|wāw}}'' (representing {{IPA|/uː/}}) is extremely rare, to the point that ''{{transl|ar|DIN|yāʾ}}'' with ''{{transl|ar|DIN|sukūn}}'' will be unambiguously read as the [[diphthong]] {{IPA|/aj/}}, and ''{{transl|ar|DIN|wāw}}'' with ''{{transl|ar|DIN|sukūn}}'' will be read {{IPA|/aw/}}. For example, the letters ''{{transl|ar|m-w-s-y-q-ā}}'' ({{rtl-lang|ar|موسيقى}} with an ''{{transl|ar|DIN|ʾalif maqṣūrah}}'' at the end of the word)
will be read most naturally as the word ''{{transl|ar|DIN|mūsīqā}}'' (&quot;music&quot;).  If one were to write a ''{{transl|ar|DIN|sukūn}}'' above the ''{{transl|ar|DIN|wāw}}'', the ''{{transl|ar|DIN|yāʾ}}'' and the ''{{transl|ar|DIN|ʾalif}}'', one would get {{rtl-lang|ar|موْسيْقىْ}}, which would be read as  ''{{transl|ar|*mawsaykāy}}'' (note however that the final ''{{transl|ar|DIN|ʾalif maqṣūrah}}'', because it is an ''{{transl|ar|DIN|ʾalif}}'', never takes a ''{{transl|ar|DIN|sukūn}}'').  The word, entirely vocalized, would be written as {{rtl-lang|ar|مُوسِيقَى}}.  The Koranic spelling would have no ''{{transl|ar|DIN|sukūn}}'' sign above the final ''{{transl|ar|DIN|ʾalif maqṣūrah}}'', but instead a miniature ''{{transl|ar|DIN|ʾalif}}'' above the preceding ''{{transl|ar|DIN|qāf}}'' consonant, which is a valid [[Unicode]] character but most Arabic computer fonts cannot in fact display this miniature ''{{transl|ar|DIN|ʾalif}}'' as of 2006.

No ''{{transl|ar|DIN|sukūn}}'' is placed on word-final consonants, even if no vowel is pronounced, because fully vocalized texts are always written as if  the ''[[ʾIʿrab|{{transl|ar|DIN|ʾIʿrāb}}]]'' vowels were in fact pronounced.  For example, ''{{transl|ar|DIN|ʾAḥmad zawǧ šarrīr}}'', meaning “Ahmed is a wicked husband”, for the purposes of Arabic grammar and orthography, is treated as if still pronounced with full ''{{transl|ar|DIN|ʾIʿrāb}}'', i.e. ''{{transl|ar|ʾAḥmadu zawǧun šarrirun}}'' with the complete [[desinence]]s.

