|{{transl|ar|DIN|sukūn}}
|(no vowel with this consonant letter or&lt;br /&gt;diphthong with this long vowel letter)
|Ø
|- style=&quot;text-align:center;&quot;
|style=&quot;line-height:180%;padding:10px;&quot;|&lt;small&gt;0670&lt;/small&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;font size=&quot;5&quot;&gt;{{rtl-lang|ar|  ٰ  }}&lt;/font&gt;&lt;sup&gt;&lt;small style=&quot;color:#ccc;&quot;&gt;◌&lt;/small&gt;&lt;/sup&gt;
|{{transl|ar|DIN|ʾalif}} above
|''{{transl|ar|DIN|ā}}''
|{{IPA|/aː/}}
|}

The ''{{transl|ar|DIN|sukūn}}'' is also used for transliterating words into the Arabic script. The Persian word {{rtl-lang|fa|ماسک}} (''mâsk'', from the English word &quot;mask&quot;), for example, might be written with a ''{{transl|ar|DIN|sukūn}}'' above the {{rtl-lang|fa|ﺱ}}  to signify that there is no vowel sound between that letter and the {{rtl-lang|fa|ک}}.

==Additional letters==&lt;!--If any are missing, please add them.--&gt;

Additional modified letters, used in non-Arabic languages, or in Arabic for transliterating foreign words only, include:
&lt;!-- This would look nicer in tables. --&gt;

===Additions used in Arabic dialects===

*&lt;big&gt;{{unicode|[[چ]]}}&lt;/big&gt; — ''Tche'', used mostly in the Iraqi Arabic and rarely in the Maghrebi spelling for {{IPA|[t͡ʃ]}} sound.

*&lt;big&gt;{{unicode|ڜ}}&lt;/big&gt; — a Maghrebi letter for {{IPA|[t͡ʃ]}}.

*&lt;big&gt;{{unicode|ڢ}}&lt;/big&gt; — a [[Pe_(letter)#Arabic_fa|Maghrebi]] variation of standard letter {{unicode|ف}}.

*[[File:Qaf Maghribi.svg|12px]] and &lt;big&gt;{{unicode|ف/ڧ}}&lt;/big&gt; — a [[ق#Arabic_qaf|Maghrebi]] variation of standard letter {{unicode|ق}} (as a rule, dotless in isolated and final positions and dotted in the initial and medial forms).

*&lt;big&gt;{{unicode|ڨ}}&lt;/big&gt; — a Maghrebi letter, sometimes used for {{IPA|[g]}}.

*&lt;big&gt;{{unicode|[[گ]]}}&lt;/big&gt; — the ''gāf'' letter used in the Iraqi Arabic for {{IPA|[g]}}.

===Sometimes used for writing foreign words===
*&lt;big&gt;[[ڤ]]&lt;/big&gt; - ''Ve'', sometimes used to represent the sound {{IPA|[v]}} when transliterating foreign words in Arabic. Also used in writing [[Varieties of Arabic|dialects]] with that sound.&lt;ref name=dialecttutorial&gt;[http://www1.ccls.columbia.edu/~cadim/ArabicDialectTutorialAMTA2006.pdf Arabic Dialect Tutorial]&lt;/ref&gt; Normally the letter &lt;big&gt;[[ف]]&lt;/big&gt; - ''{{transl|ar|fāʾ}}'' - is used to transliterate {{IPA|[v]}}. Also used as ''pa'' in the [[Jawi script]]. In [[Tunisia]] a character similar to ''ve'' in its initial and medial forms is sometimes used to represent the phoneme {{IPA|[ɡ]}}. In final and isolate form it has the form {{unicode|ڨ}}[[File:Tunisian-gaf.svg|11px]] which resembles the letter ''{{transl|ar|DIN|qāf}}'' whence it is derived. The sound {{IPA|[v]}} in Tunisia and some other regions of Maghreb is rendered using the Arabic letter ''{{transl|ar|fāʾ}}'' with three dots underneath &lt;big&gt;{{unicode|ڥ}}&lt;/big&gt;.
**Also used in [[Kurdish language|Kurdish]]. &lt;!--If any, add more languages. --&gt;

*&lt;big&gt;[[پ]]&lt;/big&gt; - ''Pe'', used to represent the sound {{IPA|[p]}} in [[Persian language|Persian]], [[Urdu language|Urdu]], and [[Kurdish language|Kurdish]]; sometimes used to represent the letter {{IPA|[p]}} when transliterating foreign words in Arabic, although Arabic nearly always substitutes {{IPA|[b]}} for {{IPA|[p]}} in the transliteration of foreign terms.  Normally the letter &lt;big&gt;[[ب]]&lt;/big&gt; - ''{{transl|ar|bāʾ}}'' - is used to transliterate {{IPA|[p]}}. So, &quot;[[7up]]&quot; can be transcribed as  &lt;big&gt;{{rtl-lang|ar|سفن أب}}&lt;/big&gt; or {{Script/Arabic|سڤن أﭖ}}.
**Also used in [[Persian language|Persian]], and [[Urdu language|Urdu]]. &lt;!--If any, add more languages. --&gt;

*&lt;big&gt;[[چ]]&lt;/big&gt; - ''Che'', used to represent {{IPAblink|tʃ}} (&quot;ch&quot;). It is used in [[Persian language|Persian]], [[Urdu language|Urdu]], and [[Kurdish language|Kurdish]] and sometimes used when transliterating foreign words in Arabic. In the Iraqi spoken dialect this is often used, especially when referring in the feminine, although it is rarely written.  Nevertheless, Arabic usually substitutes other letters in the transliteration of foreign terms: normally the combination &lt;big&gt;{{rtl-lang|ar|تش}}&lt;/big&gt; - ''{{transl|ar|DIN|tāʾ}}'' and ''{{transl|ar|DIN|šīn}}'' - is used to transliterate the {{IPA|/tʃ/}} sound, as in &quot;[[Chad]]&quot;. In Egypt &lt;big&gt;چ&lt;/big&gt; is used for {{IPA|[ʒ]}} (or {{IPA|/dʒ/}}, which is approximated to {{IPA|[ʒ]}}).
**''Ca'' in the [[Jawi script]].&lt;!--If any, add more languages. --&gt;

*&lt;big&gt;[[گ]]&lt;/big&gt; - ''{{transl|ar|Gāf}}'', used to represent the {{IPA|[ɡ]}} sound (as in &quot;get&quot;). Normally used in [[Persian alphabet|Persian]], [[Kurdish alphabet|Kurdish]], and Urdu. Often foreign words with {{IPA|[ɡ]}} are transliterated in Arabic with &lt;big&gt;[[ك]]&lt;/big&gt; (''{{transl|ar|DIN|kāf}}''), &lt;big&gt;[[غ]]&lt;/big&gt; (''{{transl|ar|DIN|ġayn}}'') or &lt;big&gt;[[ج]]&lt;/big&gt; (''{{transl|ar|DIN|ǧīm}}''), which may or may not change the original sound. In Egypt &lt;big&gt;ج&lt;/big&gt; is normally pronounced {{IPA|[ɡ]}}.
**Also used in [[Persian language|Persian]], [[Urdu language|Urdu]], and [[Bedouin]] dialects.&lt;ref name=dialecttutorial/&gt; &lt;!--If any, add more languages. --&gt;

*&lt;big&gt;[[ژ]]&lt;/big&gt; - ''{{transl|ar|Že/zhe}}'', used to represent the [[voiced postalveolar fricative]] {{IPAblink|ʒ}} in, [[Persian Language|Persian]], [[Kurdish language|Kurdish]], [[Urdu alphabet|Urdu]] and [[Uyghur language|Uyghur]]. This is used to transliterate words of foreign origin, mostly French, in [[Levantine Arabic|Levantine]] and [[Maghrebi Arabic]] dialects. In Egypt &lt;big&gt;[[چ]]&lt;/big&gt; is used for {{IPAblink|ʒ}} (or {{IPA|/dʒ/}}, which is approximated to {{IPAblink|ʒ}}). In the Leavant and northwest  Africa (except Algeria), &lt;big&gt;[[ج]]&lt;/big&gt; is normally pronounced {{IPAblink|ʒ}}, so it is used to transcribe that sound. &lt;big&gt;[[ش]]&lt;/big&gt; might be used instead as well.
**Also used in [[Persian language|Persian]], and [[Urdu language|Urdu]]. &lt;!--If any, add more languages. --&gt;

*In addition, when transliterating [[Spanish language|Spanish]] or [[Italian language|Italian]], Arabic language speakers write out most or all the vowels as long (''{{transl|ar|DIN|ā}}'' with ''{{transl|ar|DIN|ʾalif}}'', ''ē''&lt;!--not DIN 31635 standard--&gt; and ''{{transl|ar|DIN|ī}}'' with ''{{transl|ar|DIN|yaʾ}}'', and ''ō''&lt;!--not DIN 31635 standard--&gt; and ''{{transl|ar|DIN|ū}}'' with ''{{transl|ar|DIN|wāw}}''), meaning it approaches a true alphabet.

===Used in languages other than Arabic===
[[File:WritingSystemsoftheWorld4.png|thumb|right|400px|Writings of the world.]]

*&lt;big&gt;{{unicode|[[Ng (Arabic)|ڭ]]}}&lt;/big&gt; - Ng, used to represent the {{IPAblink|ŋ}} phoneme in [[Ottoman Turkish language|Ottoman Turkish]], [[Kazakh language|Kazakh]], [[Kyrgyz language|Kyrgyz]], and [[Uyghur language|Uyghur]].

*&lt;big&gt;{{unicode|[[ݙ]]}}&lt;/big&gt; - used in [[Saraiki language|Siraiki]] to represent a [[voiced retroflex implosive]] {{IPA|[ɗ̢]}}.

*&lt;big&gt;{{unicode|[[ݐ]]}}&lt;/big&gt; - used to represent the equivalent of the Latin letter [[Ƴ]] ([[palatalization|palatalized]] [[glottal stop]] {{IPA|[ʔʲ]}}) in some African languages such as [[Fula language|Fulfulde]].

*&lt;big&gt;{{unicode|[[ݫ]]}}&lt;/big&gt; - used in [[Ormuri]] to represent a [[voiced alveolo-palatal fricative]] {{IPA|[ʑ]}}, as well as in [[Torwali]].

*&lt;big&gt;{{unicode|[[ݭ]]}}&lt;/big&gt; - used in [[Kalami]] to represent a [[voiceless retroflex fricative]] {{IPA|[ʂ]}}, and in [[Ormuri]] to represent a voiceless alveolo-palatal fricative.

*&lt;big&gt;{{unicode|[[ݜ]]}}&lt;/big&gt; - used in [[Shina language|Shina]] to represent a [[voiceless retroflex fricative]] {{IPA|[ʂ]}}.

*&lt;big&gt;{{unicode|[[ݪ]]}}&lt;/big&gt; - used in [[Marwari language|Marwari]] to represent a [[retroflex lateral flap]] {{IPA|[ɺ̢]}}, and in [[Kalami]] to represent a [[voiceless lateral fricative]] {{IPA|[ɬ]}}.

*&lt;big&gt;{{unicode|[[B̤ē|ﭒ]]}}&lt;/big&gt; - {{unicode|B̤ē}}, used to represent a [[voiced bilabial implosive]] {{IPA|[ɓ]}} in [[Hausa language|Hausa]] and [[Sindhi language|Sindhi]].

*&lt;big&gt;{{unicode|[[ﭞ]]}}&lt;/big&gt; - {{unicode|Ṭhē}}, represents the aspirated [[voiceless retroflex plosive]] {{IPA|[ʈʰ]}} in [[Sindhi language|Sindhi]].

*&lt;big&gt;[[Khē|ﮎ]]&lt;/big&gt; - Khē, represents {{IPA|[kʰ]}} in [[Sindhi language|Sindhi]].

*&lt;big&gt;[[Ṭe|ﭦ]]&lt;/big&gt; - {{unicode|Ṭe}}, used to represent {{unicode|Ṭ}} (a [[voiceless retroflex plosive]] {{IPA|[ʈ]}}) in [[Urdu alphabet|Urdu]].

*&lt;big&gt;{{unicode|[[ڳ]]}}&lt;/big&gt; - represents a [[voiced velar implosive]] {{IPA|/ɠ/}} in [[Sindhi language|Sindhi]]

*&lt;big&gt;{{unicode|[[ڱ]]}}&lt;/big&gt; - represents the [[Velar nasal]] {{IPA|/ŋ/}} phoneme in [[Sindhi language|Sindhi]].

*&lt;big&gt;{{unicode|[[ڻ]]}}&lt;/big&gt; - represents the [[retroflex nasal]] {{IPA|/ɳ/}} phoneme in [[Sindhi language|Sindhi]].

*&lt;big&gt;{{unicode|[[ڀ]]}}&lt;/big&gt; - represents an aspirated [[voiced bilabial plosive]] {{IPA|[bʱ]}} in [[Sindhi language|Sindhi]].

*&lt;big&gt;[[ژ]]&lt;/big&gt; - ''Zhe'', represents a [[voiced postalveolar fricative]] {{IPA|[ʒ]}} in [[Persian language|Persian]], [[Urdu alphabet|Urdu]], [[Kurdish language|Kurdish]], and [[Uyghur language|Uyghur]].

*&lt;big&gt;[[ڑ]]&lt;/big&gt; - {{unicode|Aṛ}}, represents a [[retroflex flap]] {{IPA|[ɽ]}} in [[Urdu alphabet|Urdu]].

*&lt;big&gt;{{unicode|[[ڕ]]}}&lt;/big&gt; - used in [[kurdish language|Kurdish]] to represent rr {{IPA|[r]}} in ''Yekgirtú'' spelling.

*&lt;big&gt;[[Gaf|گ]]&lt;/big&gt; - Gaf, represents a [[voiced velar plosive]] {{IPA|[ɡ]}} in [[Iraqi Arabic]], [[Persian language|Persian]], [[Urdu language|Urdu]], [[Kyrgyz language|Kyrgyz]], [[Kazakh language|Kazakh]], [[Kurdish language|Kurdish]], [[Uyghur language|Uyghur]], and [[Ottoman Turkish language|Ottoman Turkish]].

*&lt;big&gt;{{unicode|[[Gaf|ݣ]]}}&lt;/big&gt; - Gaf, represents a [[voiced velar plosive]] {{IPA|[ɡ]}} in informal [[Moroccan Arabic]], as well as officially to transliterate the letter {{IPA|[ɡ]}} in many city names such as [[Agadir]] ({{script/Arabic|أݣادير}}), and family names such as El Guerrouj ({{script/Arabic|الݣروج}}).

*&lt;big&gt;{{unicode|[[Gaf|ݢ]]}}&lt;/big&gt; or &lt;big&gt;[[Gaf|ڬ]]&lt;/big&gt; - Gaf, represents a [[voiced velar plosive]] {{IPA|[ɡ]}} in the [[Jawi script]] of [[Malay language|Malay]].

*&lt;big&gt;[[ے]]&lt;/big&gt; - Bari ye, represents &quot;ai&quot; or &quot;e&quot; in [[Urdu alphabet|Urdu]] [{{IPAlink|ɛː}}, {{IPAlink|eː}}] and [[Punjabi language|Punjabi]].

*&lt;big&gt;{{unicode|[[ێ]]}}&lt;/big&gt; - represents Ê or É {{IPAblink|e}} in [[Kurdish language|Kurdish]].

*&lt;big&gt;{{unicode|[[ۆ]]}}&lt;/big&gt; - represents O {{IPAblink|o}} in [[Kurdish language|Kurdish]], and in [[Uyghur language|Uyghur]] it represents the sound similar to the French eu and œu {{IPAblink|ø}} sound

*&lt;big&gt;{{unicode|[[ۋ]]}}&lt;/big&gt; - represents a [[voiced labiodental fricative]] {{IPA|[v]}} in [[Kyrgyz language|Kyrgyz]], Uyghur, and Old Tatar; and  {{IPA|/w, ʊw, ʉw/}} in [[Kazakh language|Kazakh]]; also formerly used in [[Nogai language#Alphabet|Nogai]].

*&lt;big&gt;{{unicode|[[ڽ]]}}&lt;/big&gt; - ''Nya'' in the [[Jawi script]].

*&lt;big&gt;{{unicode|[[ڠ]]}}&lt;/big&gt; - ''Nga'' in the [[Jawi script]].

*&lt;big&gt;{{unicode|[[ۏ]]}}&lt;/big&gt; - ''Va'' in the [[Jawi script]].

*&lt;big&gt;{{unicode|[[ڈ]]}}&lt;/big&gt; - {{unicode|[[Ḍ]]}} {{IPAblink|ɖ}} in [[Urdu alphabet|Urdu]].

==  Numerals  ==
{{Main|Arabic numerals}}

There are two kinds of numerals used in Arabic writing; standard numerals{{Clarify|date=June 2009|reason=explain or wikilink &quot;standard numeral&quot;: what are they? The same as the western numerals 1,2,3, and so forth?}} (predominant in the [[Arab World]]), and [[Eastern Arabic numerals]] (used in [[Iran]], [[Afghanistan]], [[Pakistan]] and [[India]]).  In Arabic, the former are referred to as &quot;Indian numbers&quot; (''{{transl|ar|DIN|ʾarqām hindiyyah}}'', {{rtl-lang|ar|أرقام هندية}}).  Arabic (or Hindu-Arabic) numerals are also used in Europe and the rest of the [[Western World]] in a third variant, the Western Arabic numerals, even though the Arabic alphabet is not. In most of present-day North Africa, the usual western numerals are used; in medieval times, a slightly different set was used, from which Western Arabic numerals derive, via Italy. Like Arabic alphabetic characters, Arabic numerals are written from right to left, though the units are always right-most, and the highest value left-most, just as with Western &quot;Arabic numerals&quot;. Telephone numbers are read from left to right.

{| class=&quot;wikitable&quot; style=&quot;text-align:center;&quot;
