| MC = 92/100&lt;ref name=&quot;mcscores&quot;/&gt;
}}

The game showed well at the 1998 [[Electronic Entertainment Expo]] (E3).&lt;ref name=SMACManual1999p240&gt;[[#SMACManual1999|Reynolds (1998-11-23)]], p.240.&lt;/ref&gt; Walter Morbeck of GameSpot said that ''SMAC'' was &quot;more than hi-tech physics and new ways to blow each other up,&quot; and that the game would feature realistic aliens.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web| url = http://www.e3news.com/pc/centauri/index.html| title = Sid Meier's Alpha Centauri| publisher = GameSpot| first = Walter| last = Morbeck| date = 1998-06-03| archivedate = 1999-01-28| archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/19990128233315/www.e3news.com/pc/centauri/index.html}}&lt;/ref&gt; Terry Coleman of ''Computer Gaming World'' predicted that ''SMAC'' would be &quot;another huge hit&quot;.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url = http://www.e3news.com/pc/centauri/index2.html| archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/19990129011712/www.e3news.com/pc/centauri/index2.html| title=GameSpot's E3 News - Sid Meier's Alpha Centauri| publisher=GameSpot| first = Terry| last = Coleman| date= 1998-06-03| archivedate = 1999-01-29| accessdate=2010-09-16}}&lt;/ref&gt; OGR awarded it &quot;Most Promising Strategy Game&quot; and one of the top 25 games of E3 '98.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web| url=http://www.ogr.com/specials/bestofe3/e3awards.html| archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/19990203073840/www.ogr.com/specials/bestofe3/e3awards.html| title=Specials - Best of E3 Expo '98| publisher=OGR.com| year = 1998| archivedate=1999-02-03| accessdate=2010-09-16}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web| url=http://www.ogr.com/specials/bestofe3/best_of_e3.shtml| archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/19990203031205/www.ogr.com/specials/bestofe3/best_of_e3.shtml| title=Specials - Best of E3 Expo '98| publisher=OGR.com| year = 1998| archivedate=1999-02-03| accessdate=2010-09-16}}&lt;/ref&gt; In a vote of 27&amp;nbsp;journalists from 22&amp;nbsp;gaming magazine, ''SMAC'' won &quot;Best Turn Based Strategy&quot; of E3 Show Award.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web| url = http://www.e3.net/1998/award/details.html| title = UGO Best of E3 Show Award Winners| publisher = UGO Networks| year = 1998| archivedate = 1999-02-21|archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/19990221124201/www.e3.net/1998/award/details.html}}&lt;/ref&gt; Aaron John Loeb, the Awards Committee Chairman, said &quot;for those that understand the intricacies, the wonder, the glory of turn based 'culture building,' this is the game worth skipping class for.&quot;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.e3.net/1998/award/alphacentauri.html| archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/19981201232145/www.e3.net/1998/award/alphacentauri.html| title=Best of E3 Show Awards - 1998| publisher=UGO| year = 1998| archivedate= 1998-12-01| accessdate=2010-09-16}}&lt;/ref&gt;

''Alpha Centauri's'' science fiction storyline received high praise; IGN considered the game an exception to PC sc-fi cliches,&lt;ref name=&quot;ignreview&quot; /&gt; and ''GamePro'' compared the plot to the works of writers [[Stanley Kubrick]] and [[Isaac Asimov]].&lt;ref name=&quot;gproreview&quot; /&gt; J.C. Herz of ''The New York Times'' suggested that the game was a marriage of ''[[SimCity]]'' and [[Frank Herbert]]'s ''[[Dune (book)|Dune]]''.&lt;ref name=&quot;nytimes&quot;&gt;{{cite news|last=Herz|first=J.C.|title=Game Theory; On 2067 Battleground, 1999 Political Passions|url=http://www.nytimes.com/1999/03/18/technology/game-theory-on-2067-battleground-1999-political-passions.html|publisher=The New York Times|accessdate=2010-06-22 | date=1999-03-18}}&lt;/ref&gt; ''GamePro''{{'}}s Dan Morris said &quot;As the single-player campaign builds to its final showdown, the ramifications of the final theoretical discoveries elevate Alpha Centauri from great strategy game to science-fiction epic.&quot;&lt;ref name=&quot;gproreview&quot; /&gt; Game Revolution said, &quot;The well crafted story, admirable science-fiction world, fully realized scenario, and quality core gameplay are sure to please.&quot;&lt;ref name=&quot;grevreview&quot;&gt;{{cite web|last=B|first=Johnny|title=Alpha Centauri Review for the PC|url=http://www.gamerevolution.com/review/pc/alpha-centauri|publisher=Game Revolution|accessdate=2010-06-22}}&lt;/ref&gt; ''Edge'' praised the uniqueness of expression saying it was &quot;the same kind of old-fashioned, consensual storytelling that once drew universes out of ASCII.&quot; &lt;ref name=Edge2006p1/&gt; The in-game writing and faction leaders were also well-received for their believability, especially the voice acting.&lt;ref name=Tito2005p1/&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;ignreview&quot; /&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;fsquadreview&quot; /&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;avaultreview&quot;&gt;{{cite web|last=Hines|first=Pete|title=Sid Meier's Alpha Centauri PC Review|url=http://www.avault.com/reviews/pc/sid-meiers-alpha-centauri-pc-review/|publisher=The Adrenaline Vault|accessdate=2010-06-22}}&lt;/ref&gt; GameSpot reviewer Denny Atkin called the factions and their abilities ''Alpha Centauri''{{'}}s &quot;most impressive aspect&quot;.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web| url = http://www.gamespot.com/pc/strategy/sidmeiersalphacentauri/review.html| title = Sid Meier's Alpha Centauri Review| first = Denny| last = Atkin| publisher = GameSpot| date = 1999-02-19| accessdate = 2011-03-01}}&lt;/ref&gt; Greg Tito of The Escapist said, &quot;the genius of the game is how it flawlessly blends its great writing with strategy elements.&quot;&lt;ref name=Tito2005p2/&gt;

''Alpha Centauri's'' turn-based gameplay, including the technology trees and factional warfare, was commonly compared to ''Civilization'' and ''Civilization II''. The Adrenaline Vault's Pete Hines said, &quot;While SMAC is the evolutionary off-spring to Civ and Civ 2, it is not Civ 2 in space. Although the comparison is inevitable because of the lineage, it is still short-sighted.&quot;&lt;ref name=&quot;avaultreview&quot; /&gt; ''Edge'' in 2006 praised &quot;Alpha Centauri’s greater sophistications as a strategy game.&quot; &lt;ref name=Edge2006p1/&gt; IGN said &quot;Alpha Centauri is a better game than Civilization II; it's deep, rich, rewarding, thought-provoking in almost every way.&quot;&lt;ref name=&quot;ignreview&quot; /&gt; Game Revolution's reviewer was less magnanimous, saying &quot;Alpha Centauri is at least as good a game as Civilization 2. But it is its great similarity that also does it the most detriment. Alpha Centauri simply does not do enough that is new; it just doesn't innovate enough to earn a higher grade.&quot;&lt;ref name=&quot;grevreview&quot; /&gt; The ability to create custom units was praised,&lt;ref name=&quot;fsquadreview&quot; /&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;avaultreview&quot; /&gt; as was the depth of the tech tree.&lt;ref name=&quot;avaultreview&quot; /&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;grevreview&quot; /&gt; The artificial intelligence of computer-controlled factions, which featured adaptability and behavioral subtlety,&lt;ref name=&quot;redefining&quot;&gt;{{Cite news | last = Scheisel | first = Seth | authorlink = | title = Redefining the Power of the Gamer | work = The New York Times | publisher = | date = June 7, 2005 | url = http://www.nytimes.com/2005/06/07/arts/07arti.html | accessdate = November 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt; was given mixed comments; some reviewers thought it was efficient and logical,&lt;ref name=&quot;ignreview&quot; /&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;gproreview&quot; /&gt; while others found it confusing or erratic.&lt;ref name=&quot;avaultreview&quot; /&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;grevreview&quot; /&gt; ''Edge'' was disappointed in the game's diplomacy, finding &quot;no more and no less than is expected from the genre&quot; and unhappy with &quot;the inability to sound out any real sense of relationship or rational discourse.&quot; &lt;ref name=Edge2006p2/&gt;

{{Rquote|left|If you're looking for gratuitous eye candy, then you're obviously in the wrong place. Alpha Centauri's graphics are quite good, but they're not going to make anyone sit up and take notice.|Bob Colayco|FiringSquad&lt;ref name=&quot;fsquadreview&quot; /&gt;}}

The game's graphics were widely acknowledged to be above average at the time of its release, but not revolutionary.&lt;ref name=&quot;ignreview&quot; /&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;fsquadreview&quot; /&gt; Its maps and interface were
considered detailed and in accordance with a space theme,&lt;ref name=&quot;fsquadreview&quot; /&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;grevreview&quot; /&gt; but the game was released with a limited color palette.&lt;ref name=&quot;avaultreview&quot; /&gt; The in-game cutscenes, particularly the [[full motion video]] that accompanied technological advances, were praised for their quality and innovation.&lt;ref name=&quot;fsquadreview&quot; /&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;avaultreview&quot; /&gt; ''Alpha Centauri's'' sound and music received similar comments;&lt;ref name=&quot;ignreview&quot; /&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;avaultreview&quot; /&gt; FiringSquad said &quot;&lt;nowiki&gt;[The sound effect quality]&lt;/nowiki&gt; sort of follows the same line as the unit graphics - not too splashy but enough to get the job done.&quot;&lt;ref name=&quot;fsquadreview&quot; /&gt;

''Alpha Centauri'' has won several Game of the Year awards,&lt;ref name=Tito2005p2/&gt; including those from the ''[[The Denver Post|Denver Post]]'' and the ''[[Toronto Sun]]''. It won the &quot;Turn-based Strategy Game of the Year&quot; award from [[GameSpot]] as well. The [[Academy of Interactive Arts &amp; Sciences]] named ''Alpha Centauri'' the best strategy game of the year, and in 2000, ''Alpha Centauri'' won the [[Origins Award]] for ''Best Strategy Computer Game of 1999''.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web| url=http://www.firaxis.com/smac/game.cfm| title=Sid Meier's Alpha Centauri: The Game| publisher=Firaxis| archivedate = 2008-01-24| archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20080124172058/www.firaxis.com/smac/game.cfm}}&lt;/ref&gt; ''Alpha Centauri'' has the distinction of receiving gaming magazine ''[[PC Gamer]]''{{'}}s highest score (98%),&lt;ref name=Tito2005p2/&gt; surpassing ''Civilization II''{{'}}s score (97%).&lt;ref name=&quot;pcgamer&quot;&gt;{{Cite journal|journal=PC Gamer|year=1999|month=April}}&lt;/ref&gt;

==Legacy==
{{Infobox book series
|name = Sid Meier's Alpha Centauri
|collapsible = yes
|state = collapsed
|title_orig =
|author = [[Michael Ely]]
|illustrator =
|cover_artist =
|translator =
|country = [[United States]]
|language = [[English language|English]]
|genre = [[Science fiction]]
|publisher = Simon &amp; Schuster
|pub_date =
|english_pub_date =
|media_type = Print ([[Paperback]])
|preceded by =
|followed by =
}}

After the release of the expansion, multimedia producer [[Michael Ely]] wrote a trilogy of novels based on the game. Illustrator [[Rafael Kayanan]] also wrote a [[graphic novel]] entitled ''Alpha Centauri: Power of the Mindworms''.&lt;ref name=&quot;OfficialSiteStory&quot;/&gt;

While not a direct sequel of ''Civilization II'', ''Alpha Centauri'' is considered a spiritual successor because it shares the same general principles and was made by many of the original developers. There have been no sequels beyond ''SMAX'', something that writer Greg Tito attributed to Reynolds leaving Firaxis in 2000 to form [[Big Huge Games]].&lt;ref name=Tito2005p2/&gt; ''SMAX'' producer and lead designer Timothy Train also left Firaxis with Reynolds.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.allgame.com/company.php?id=494 |title=Firaxis Games |publisher=Allgame.com |date= |accessdate=2010-08-07}}&lt;/ref&gt;

Many of the features introduced in ''SMAC'' were carried over into subsequent ''Civilization'' titles.&lt;ref name=Tito2005p2/&gt; For example, each civilization's characteristics in ''Civilization III'' are reminiscent of faction bonuses and penalties,&lt;ref name=Tito2005p2/&gt; the government system in ''[[Civilization IV]]'' closely resembles ''Alpha Centauri''{{'}}s,&lt;ref name=Tito2005p2/&gt; and ''[[Civilization V]]'' includes a new win condition: the completion of the Utopia project, which is reminiscent of the Ascent to Transcendence secret project.&lt;ref&gt;[[#Edwards2010|Edwards (2010)]].&lt;/ref&gt;

Upon its release, ''Civilization III'' was compared negatively to ''Alpha Centauri'',&lt;ref name=&quot;NewSeason&quot;&gt;{{cite news | last = Schiesel | first = Seth | authorlink = | title = The New Season Video Games; Going to War in the Matrix, Middle Earth, or the Bronx | work = The New York Times | publisher = | date = September 11, 2005 | url = http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9F06E3DA1431F932A2575AC0A9639C8B63 | accessdate = November 6, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt; while ''Edge'' magazine noted that ''Alpha Centauri'' remained &quot;highly regarded&quot; in 2006.&lt;ref name=Edge2006p2/&gt; [[Steve Jackson Games]] published ''GURPS Alpha Centauri'', a sourcebook for the [[GURPS]] [[role-playing game (pen and paper)|role-playing game]] set in the ''Alpha Centauri'' universe.&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.sjgames.com/gurps/books/alphacentauri/ Official homepage]&lt;/ref&gt; On May 7, 2010, Brendan Casey released an unofficial [[Patch (computing)|patch]], which fixes bugs in ''Alpha Centauri''.&lt;ref&gt;Casey, Brendan (also known as scient, 2010) [http://www.civgaming.net/forums/showthread.php?p=162396#post162396 &quot;Unofficial SMAC/X Patches Version 1.0&quot;], Civilization Gaming Networks Forums, May 7, 2010.&lt;/ref&gt; His project began in February 2009 at Apolyton's Alpha Centauri site&lt;ref&gt;Casey, Brendan (2009) [http://www.apolyton.net/forums/showthread.php?p=5531636#post5531636 &quot;Fixing SMACX Bugs&quot;], Apolyton Civilizations Site Forums, February 13, 2009.&lt;/ref&gt; and moved in June 2009 to the Civilization Gaming Network,&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.civgaming.net/forums/showthread.php?p=161019#post161019 &quot;Orientation and Moderation&quot;], Civilization Gaming Networks Forums, June 19, 2009.&lt;/ref&gt; where he plans to continue developing further patch versions.&lt;ref&gt;WePlayCiv [http://www.weplayciv.com//node/233 &quot;Sid Meier's Alpha Centauri / Alien Crossfire Unofficial Patch released!&quot;], ''WePlayCiv'', May 14, 2010.&lt;/ref&gt; [[Sold-Out Software]] also re-released the game.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|author=Fink |url=http://www.mastertronic.com/productSoldOut.asp?pid=756&amp;productLabelID=1 |title=Sid Meier's Alpha Centauri Complete |publisher=Mastertronic |date= |accessdate=2011-01-25}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;!--Is the re-release of the game ten years later really part of Legacy or is this WP:INDISCRIMINATE?--&gt;

